Recent Achievements

1. Enhanced CSV Output

  • Context-Aware Sorting: Cards are now sorted logically based on the best game type (e.g., Null games sort A-K-Q…, Suit games sort J-A-10…).
  • WonMask: Added a WonMask column (e.g., G--H-N) indicating which game types are winnable (>66%) for a given hand.
  • BestGame Selection: Refined logic to prefer Grand over Suit games and Null over simple Diamond games (based on game value) when win probabilities are equal.

2. Simulation & Server Migration

  • Bash Script: Created research/run_general_sim_50k.sh for running large-scale simulations on Ubuntu servers.
  • Server Status: Created check_server_status.ps1 to monitor the remote simulation via SSH (checks process status and progress %).
  • Data Retrieval: Created fetch_server_results.ps1 to easily copy results to local machine.

3. Biddability Analysis (“Bid or Pass”)

  • Analyzed 1000 hands to determine “Reizbarkeit”.
  • Rules of Thumb:
    • 2 Jacks: >50% Win Chance.
    • Power 5: (Jacks + Aces + Tens >= 5) -> >50% Win Chance.
    • Safe Zone: 3 Jacks or Power 6+ (>80%).
  • Artifact: rules_of_thumb.md.

4. Detailed Strength Analysis by Trump Count

Comprehensive analysis of hand strength, grouped by total length (Suit + Jacks). Sub-categories: 1. Pre-Discard: Biddability of the initial 10 cards. 2. Post-Discard (Grand): Final strength for Grand Games. 3. Post-Discard (Suit): Final strength for Suit Games (Clubs/Spades/etc.).

Hands with only 4 potential trumps (e.g., 1 Jack + 3 Suit, or 0 Jacks + 4 Suit). * Pre: Almost unbiddable without 3 Fulls. * Grand: Very risky. * Suit: Requires massive side strength.

6. Hand Game Strategy: The “Golden Rule”

Question: When should you play Hand instead of picking up the Skat? Assumptions: Hand Game is +33% value; Losing Skat Game is double penalty (-2x); Losing Hand Game is single penalty (-1.33x).

The expected value analysis reveals a “Decision Boundary”. You should play Hand if:

Phand > 1.125 × Pskat − 0.25

Key Decision Points: * If Skat Win is Guaranteed (100%): You need >88% Hand Win Probability to justify the risk of losing the extra points. * If Skat Win is Strong (80%): You only need >65% Hand Win Probability. The lower penalty for losing a Hand game makes it attractive even with lower odds. * If Skat Win is Shaky (60%): You only need >43% Hand Win Probability! It is statistically safer to play Hand and risk a small loss than to pick up and risk a double loss.

Interactive Decision Matrix

Specific Recommendations (Where Hand > Pickup): Comparing our data with this rule reveals specific “Blue Zones” where you should play Hand:

  • 7+ Trumps (Dominant Hands):
    • Almost ALWAYS play Hand.
    • Example: 3 Jacks + 5 Suit Cards. The win probability is ~100% for both, but Hand gives +33% value.
    • Advantage: +12.5% EV
  • 6 Trumps (Strong Hands):
    • 4 Jacks: Always Play Hand.
    • 3 Jacks + High Suit: Play Hand.
    • 2 Jacks + 5 Suit: Play Hand (96% win rate is enough).
  • 5 Trumps (The “Danger Zone”):
    • 1 Jack + 4 Suit (6 SafeFulls): Play Hand! (Win 100% vs 99%).
    • 3 Jacks + 2 Suit: Play Hand.
  • 4 Trumps (The “Desperation Zone”):
    • Surprisingly, some very weak hands favor Hand Game because the risk of picking up (and finding nothing) is too costly vs just losing a cheap Hand game.
    • 1 Jack, 0 SafeFulls: Hand 3% vs Pickup 15%.
    • Note: This is an edge case where both options are bad, but Hand minimizes the maximum loss.

5. Skat Stagnation Traps (“The Disappointment Gap”)

What happens when you rely on the Skat, but the Skat doesn’t improve your hand (“Stagnation”)? Comparing “Expected Win Rate” (Pre-Discard) vs “Realized Win Rate” (Post-Discard for stagnant hands).

Trappy Signatures (Look winning initially (>66%), but if Skat is bad, they become losing (<66%)):

Signature (Total Trumps / Jacks / Fulls) Pre-Prob Post-Prob (Stagnant) Loss
5 Trumps / 0 Jacks / 4 Fulls 69% 38% -31%
5 Trumps / 2 Jacks / 2 Fulls 69% 39% -30%
6 Trumps / 2 Jacks / 1 Full 69% 42% -27%
5 Trumps / 3 Jacks / 1 Full 76% 53% -24%

Key Insight: Hands with 5 Total Trumps (e.g. 1J+4S or 2J+3S) are often “Pre-Winners” because they hope for a 6th Trump. If they don’t get it, they crash. Interactive Chart (HTML)
